Vusi Mahlasela: Oh, Yeah.

00:47:19.734 --> 00:47:25.800
Music played quite a lot of a role
during the time of struggle in South Africa,

00:47:25.800 --> 00:47:25.967
even before myself was born.

00:47:25.967 --> 00:47:29.433
It didn't before myself I was born.

00:47:29.433 --> 00:47:32.633
There was quite a lot of music.

00:47:32.633 --> 00:47:38.200
Those organizations from the BC,
Black Consciousness Movement,

00:47:38.200 --> 00:47:43.900
example, up until it was like the UTF
and the unions and all that,

00:47:43.900 --> 00:47:47.767
there was just more drive of
the music and all that.

00:47:47.767 --> 00:47:51.333
I don't know, if you have seen
the, the film called "[inaudible]".

00:47:51.333 --> 00:47:58.567
The struggle was engaged in four parts:
music, theater, writing.

00:47:58.567 --> 00:48:03.934
And of course

00:48:03.934 --> 00:48:06.567
when I, when I was born,
when I was young,

00:48:06.567 --> 00:48:12.867
for me I didn't know that there was like trouble
in my country of injustice and so on.

00:48:12.867 --> 00:48:17.767
So I came to realize this in 1976
when the students of South Africa

00:48:17.767 --> 00:48:22.433
by [inaudible] to the language of Africans [inaudible] of oppression.

00:48:22.433 --> 00:48:25.367
Where the students wanted to
speak to the government

00:48:25.367 --> 00:48:28.500
and the answer was more bullets,
more bullets, more bullets.

00:48:28.500 --> 00:48:33.834
I was eleven years old and this
escalated to other townships as well.

00:48:33.834 --> 00:48:37.900
I remember in one [inaudible] it was
on the twenty-first of June.

00:48:37.900 --> 00:48:41.834
And there was this people marching and
a lot of music and chanting and everything

00:48:41.834 --> 00:48:43.333
and I was like: "Wow."

00:48:43.333 --> 00:48:48.400
You know and I tried to ask questions
and yeah,

00:48:48.400 --> 00:48:52.700
that's when my first political education started.

00:48:52.700 --> 00:48:56.133
And there was just quite a lot
of music all over and everything.

00:48:56.133 --> 00:49:01.633
And apart from that there has been
music that I've been hearing at home

00:49:01.633 --> 00:49:05.667
because my grandmother owned a [inaudible]
what you call the speakeasy here

00:49:05.667 --> 00:49:08.166
or I think yeah, pub.

00:49:08.166 --> 00:49:12.367
And of course there'll be some songs
that I would hear as people

00:49:12.367 --> 00:49:15.967
who would be singing in the backyard
and also [inaudible]

00:49:15.967 --> 00:49:20.567
that was not allowed to be sung
around that time.

00:49:20.567 --> 00:49:23.700
So music in many different ways
played quite,

00:49:23.700 --> 00:49:28.667
it played quite a lot of role to
encourage people to stand up,

00:49:28.667 --> 00:49:31.000
realize what
was really happening to them.

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:35.467
Through the message on the song it was telling
them what was happening around that time

00:49:35.467 --> 00:49:37.600
and what they have to do.

00:49:41.433 --> 00:49:44.700
Q: I was gonna ask about the languages
that you're singing in

00:49:44.700 --> 00:49:48.166
and how many different languages,
you, you typically do sing in

00:49:48.166 --> 00:49:51.533
and, or how many you speak and how -

00:49:51.533 --> 00:49:54.333
you think about which, which languages
to use where in your songs

00:49:54.333 --> 00:49:56.467
and how to, how to mix them together.

00:49:56.467 --> 00:49:58.734
Vusi Mahlasela: Well I sing
in several languages in my music

00:49:58.734 --> 00:50:03.600
and you know we have eleven official languages,

00:50:03.600 --> 00:50:07.834
but still there are other languages
that people speak in the country

00:50:07.834 --> 00:50:09.700
which are more dialects to other languages,

00:50:09.700 --> 00:50:14.000
but you don't find that in a book form or in print.

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:19.333
And of course when I maybe compose for them,

00:50:19.333 --> 00:50:23.100
it depends what comes first,
whether music or [laughs]

00:50:23.100 --> 00:50:27.700
and sometimes it's good when I can come,
I mean incorporate both,

00:50:27.700 --> 00:50:28.967
you know, the same time.

00:50:28.967 --> 00:50:32.900
But sometimes it's just that the message
that you want to bring across

00:50:32.900 --> 00:50:38.033
through the subjects that you are sort
of talking about, the song or poem,

00:50:38.033 --> 00:50:41.467
whether you, you, you, you like it or not,

00:50:41.467 --> 00:50:44.467
you might feel that no, I want everybody
to hear this and everything,

00:50:44.467 --> 00:50:49.166
but you find that when you try to translate it
into English it doesn't work it looks,

00:50:49.166 --> 00:50:52.533
it loses the, the meaning.

00:50:52.533 --> 00:50:56.000
So rather [inaudible]

00:50:56.000 --> 00:50:59.600
but it is something that maybe that's sort
of can work when I can order

00:50:59.600 --> 00:51:04.934
and then I put it in English as well as
everybody or Kenyan, it's, it's okay.

00:51:04.934 --> 00:51:07.433
Those are some of the things that
one sort of like really find.

00:51:07.433 --> 00:51:11.166
And the song directs you
where they want to go,

00:51:11.166 --> 00:51:15.433
and you just have to pay respect and attention

00:51:15.433 --> 00:51:19.166
and follow the way the,
way they direct you.

